        <div class="home-content">
            <div>
                <h3>Challenging the myths</h3>
                <hr />
                <div class="row-fluid">
                    <div class="span4">
                        <div>
                            <img src="~/Images/User-Profile.png" />
                        </div>
                        <hr />
                        <div>
                            <p style="color: #808080; font-size: 10pt">
                                <span style="font-family: 'Lucida Handwriting'"><b>Dr. N.W. Ebiti
                                    <br />
                                    FWACP, MTM</b></span><br />
                                <span>Center Director.</span>
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="span8" style="border-left: 2px dotted #b2b0af; padding-left: 25px;">
                        <p style="font-size: 10pt;">
                            When it comes to addiction, myths abound. Experience has shown us that the path to delivering effective evidence based addiction management services begins with challenging the common myths about addiction, confronting them with what research has shown, and “setting the records straight”. 
                            <br />
                            <br />
                            Here are some of the common myths and what science has to say about them:<br />
                            <br />
                            <strong>Addiction is a willpower problem:</strong>  Addiction occurs in the area of the brain called the mesolimbic dopamine system which is not under a person’s conscious control. This means that no matter the inner resolve, determination, or willpower an addict may have, addiction like all other chronic diseases require a form of structured intervention<br />
                            <br />
                            <strong>Addiction is a behavioral problem:</strong> Research has shown that behavioral interventions are effective in changing brain function. Therefore while it’s true that behavioral and other forms of psychotherapy are effective in managing addiction, it doesn’t change the fact that addiction is a disease, characterized by changes in brain structure and function. It should also be noted that behavioral changes are key treatment components in chronic diseases like hypertension and diabetes, yet that does not make them behavioral problems.
                            <br />
                            <br />
                            <strong>Most Addicts are bad, immoral people:</strong> Addiction is a chronic, life threatening condition which has roots in genetic susceptibility, social circumstance and personal behavior. People of every class, ethnic group, intelligence level, emotional wellness level, religious affiliation and economic class may become addicts and it has nothing to do with their moral code or lack of one.<br />
                            <br />
                            <strong>Addiction management does not work, because people relapse:</strong> Relapse is not only a possibility but is the reality with all chronic illnesses. For example, relapse rates of diseases like hypertension and diabetes or even asthma are as high, if not higher than those of addiction. This in no way means that treatment doesn’t work. Addiction management results in a reduction in the number and duration of relapses, and lowers the incidence of related problems which result in a marked improvement in the individual’s ability to function in daily life and equips the individual to better cope with the next craving.
Punishment is an effective means of managing addiction: Since the basis of addiction is a neurochemically driven brain pathology, professional management rather than punishment is the only research supported effective means of management. In some cases, punitive measures such as “warehousing”(the practice of locking addicts up for long periods of time expecting a change) has been shown to worsen the problem rather than manage it.
It would be tedious to address every single myth regarding addiction, but the summary of it all, and the basis of our practice at Milestones Addiction Management Center is this – When it comes to addiction, Recovery is possible….Challenging, but possible.

                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
